We know that gamma rays are a form of high-energy electromagnetic radiation, very similar to X-rays, although they are produced differently. In X-ray science, researchers have developed special devices called polycapillary lenses. These lenses use bundles of tiny capillaries to guide and refocus X-rays, effectively bending them toward a focal point. The result is much higher spatial resolution, since the rays that scatter off-path are redirected and concentrated at the detector.

